<TEXT>
representatives of organized labor the state 
of michigan and parts manufacturers continued their criticism of 
the us freetrade agreement with canada telling a senate panel 
it benefits big automakers but no one else 
the big three is very happy with the agreement and they 
should be said marc santucci trade representative for michigan 
where the large automakers have their headquarters it is a very 
good agreement for the companies it is not such a good agreement 
for the country 
as we become a global economy we have companies no longer 
speaking for the best interests of the country santucci told the 
senate finance committee 
but thomas hanna president of the motor vehicles manufacturers 
association which represents the major automakers called the 
treaty one that we believe advances us national interests 
while helping the industry 
the agreement which requires passage by both houses of congress 
without amendment would eliminate trade barriers between the two 
nations on a wide range of goods and services the automotive 
sector accounts for about onethird of trade between the united 
states and canada 
one provision of the agreement strongly criticized by the united 
auto workers parts makers and the michigan representative allows 
canada to retain until 1996 agreements giving preferential duty 
treatment to manufacturers from outside north america having 
canadian production 
sen donald riegle a michigan democrat and member of the 
finance committee said that provision would have effects lasting 
far beyond 1996 
it is widely acknowledged that particularly in the case of 
japanese manufacturers once a part supplier is chosen it is a 
relationship of long standing riegle said by providing 
canadian suppliers with this advantage for the next seven years 
us parts producers are cut out of future opportunities to supply 
these plants 
hanna said the manufacturers supported immediate elimination of 
duty remissions but he called the delay a compromise worth 
accepting and supporting 
a second provision the uaw and parts suppliers would like to see 
removed requires vehicles shipped dutyfree between the two nations 
to have 50 percent north american content 
the uaw believes the content figure in the agreement is not 
high enough to assure the use of locally produced engines 
transmission and other major components said steve beckman the 
international economist for the uaw 
it would allow the big three to shrink the north american 
content of their vehicles down to the new standard which is far 
below the present level he said 
the manufacturers believe a 50 percent rule of origin is 
sufficiently high to do the job it was designed to do and that 
is to ensure that the benefits of the agreement accrue to those 
companies and products which can reasonably and fairly be 
considered as canadian or american in origin hanna said 
</TEXT>
