<TEXT>
the worlds rice bowl is skimpier this year 
and the agriculture department says that could help american rice 
growers export more in the early months of the 198889 season 
world rice production from the 198788 harvests is forecast at 
304 million metric tons milled equivalent down 4 percent from 
last year the departments economic research service said friday 
weak monsoons left asian producers with limited exportable supplies 
meanwhile global rice consumption is expected to increase 3 
percent leaving world stockpiles at their lowest level relative to 
use since 1974 
recently world production shortfalls and declining stocks in 
major importing countries have led to large world imports the 
report said however world trade in 1988 is expected to decline 
18 percent because high prices and reduced supplies in major 
exporting countries have deterred imports 
the us rice supply also has tightened reflecting a 6 percent 
reduction in last years harvest 
but the departments planting survey in early march indicated 
american producers intend to boost 1988 rice plantings by 19 
percent to 28 million acres that could boost this years output 
to around 155 million hundredweight from 128 million in 1987 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and there are slightly more 
than 22 hundredweight in a ton 
us farmers will harvest rice crops at least four months 
ahead of their asian competitors the report said since the 
united states will be the major source of supply during those 
months some increased export opportunities may exist towards the 
end of 1988 
however analysts cautioned that some foreign importers if 
possible may choose to wait until the beginning of 1989 when 
prices are likely to decline during the asian harvest 
the report said some foreign importers also have been 
substituting wheat for higherpriced rice 
in addition shipments of us rice under food aid are 
expected to decrease this year because of high prices the report 
said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the agriculture departments conservation 
chief says more volunteers are needed to help carry out a massive 
program aimed at protecting the nations soil and water resources 
wilson scaling head of the soil conservation service says that 
in 1987 some 2200 volunteers provided more than 1 million worth 
of assistance to agency field offices 
this earth team he said friday put in more than 132000 
hours in helping with tree planting making inventories of 
wetlands conservation education telephoning landowners to inform 
them of the conservervation reserve program and providing clerical 
and other office work 
many of the volunteers have expertise in geology biology 
botany surveying mapping and soil and erodibility 
determinations scaling said 
under 1985 farm law farmers with highly erodible cropland must 
have a conservation plan approved by dec 31 1989 and have it 
implemented by dec 31 1994 or lose usda benefits such as price 
support loans payments and insurance 
scaling said the agency estimates that 800000 conservation 
plans still need to be developed nationwide 
anyone interested in volunteering for the earth team he said 
can call 1800the soil for the location of the local office 
volunteers receive coverage for injury claims are compensated for 
travel expenses and have their contributions made part of a 
permanent work record scaling said 
