<TEXT>
a group of union presidents and business 
leaders is seeking a thaw in labormanagement relations in part by 
encouraging experiments on employee participation in business 
decisions 
united steelworkers of america president lynn williams hailed 
the position paper endorsed friday by 19 labor leaders and 
corporate officers as a landmark in labormanagement relations 
the leaders are members of the collective bargaining forum a 
group formed in 1985 by bf goodrich co chairman john d ong and 
glenn watts president emeritus of the communication workers of 
america to increase dialogue between unions and businesses 
williams at a press conference friday conceded the strategies 
in the paper on new directions for labor and management were 
provoked in part by troubled times 
the nations unions suffered a net loss of 62000 members last 
year despite an increase of 25 million in the number of americans 
holding fulltime jobs 
the document published by the department of labor said it is 
widely recognized that american industry must enhance its 
competitiveness in world markets 
besides williams union officials on the forum included united 
automobile workers president owen bieber communication workers of 
america president morton bahr and howard samuel president of the 
industrial union department of the aflcio 
corporate officers included csx transportation co president 
john snow ameritech corp chairman william l weiss and ford motor 
chairman donald petersen 
the document encouraged labor and management to experiment with 
sharing information and participation of workers in strategic and 
management business decisions such arrangements it said could 
defuse tensions caused by unions whose positions force them to 
concentrate more on preserving current benefits than on increasing 
firms abilities to compete 
the report also said management should treat employees job 
security at the policy level considering it alongside other 
business strategies ameritechs weiss said 
but weiss said the newlydefined management responsibilities are 
by no means a oneway street unions too have to take a broader 
view of their responsibilities and of where their best interests 
lie 
the report said workers could enhance their own job security by 
taking advantage of educational opportunities and accepting new 
jobs with an employer if their old positions become obsolete 
the document was short on specifics not mentioning for 
example a sweeping trade bill on capitol hill williams and other 
labor leaders have been pushing for the bill to include a provision 
requiring companies with at least 100 employees to give 60day 
notice of plant closings or layoffs under many situations 
</TEXT>
