<TEXT>
the former underboss of the cleveland mob says 
narcotics trafficking has broken down the once ironclad obedience 
that us organized crime members had for their leaders 
angelo lonardo the former underboss of the cleveland family of 
la cosa nostra testified friday that younger members of the mob 
dont take orders like they used to 
these younger members go ahead and do things on their own 
he told the senate permanent investigations subcommittee 
lonardo blamed the breakdown on the willingness of younger 
mobsters to ignore their leaders rules against narcotics 
trafficking 
greed is causing younger members to go into narcotics without 
the knowledge of the families said the 77yearold lonardo who 
is currently in the federal witness protection program and was 
shielded from the public by a screen 
last monday a former member of the sicilian mafia told the same 
panel that drugs were causing the same problem in italy 
tommaso buscetta told the subcommittee i have seen money 
drugs and greed corrupt and destroy the cosa nostra code of honor 
and loyalty to the families 
i began to realize that drugs had changed everything the 
family loyalties and codes of respect that i had known as a mafioso 
were quickly becoming things of the past 
lonardo who testified under a grant of immunity said the mob 
leaders dont like the narcotics trade because it usually brings 
greater scrutiny from law enforcement organizations 
lonardo also testified that organized crime played a large role 
in teamsters union affairs including the elections of former 
president roy l williams and current president jackie presser 
he said he was part of a 1981 effort to line up organized crime 
support for williams successful candidacy 
and when it became clear that an indictment against williams 
would force him to step down lonardo said he traveled to chicago 
to obtain organized crimes backing of cleveland native presser 
presser who currently is under indictment was the protege 
of a man affiliated with the cleveland mob and it was felt his 
election would increase the cleveland familys prestige and 
respect lonardo said 
at teamsters headquarters in washington there was no one 
available to comment on lonardos testimony friday 
lonardo said many of the teamsters union officials were made 
inducted into organized crime families before getting their 
union positions 
they listen to the families that made them he said its 
mostly the delegates and the vice presidents they get their jobs 
through the families 
the delegates who elect the top teamsters are members of la 
cosa nostra nunn asked lonardo said that was the case 
presser who heads the cleveland local of the teamsters in 
addition to the international union is under indictment on charges 
of union racketeering and conspiracy to embezzle by having ghost 
employees on the union payroll 
presser said the fbi authorized his actions and faces trial in 
july in cleveland 
williams was convicted of offering a bribe to former sen howard 
cannon dnev in trying to block trucking deregulation 
