<TEXT>
in april 1943 poorly armed fighters in 
warsaws walled jewish ghetto appealed to poles to join them in 
their dignified but doomed struggle to turn back the nazi tide 
fortyfive years later poles and jews painfully discussed the 
response to that appeal during a remarkable twoday conference on 
struggle and martyrdom during the nazi occupation emotional wounds 
reopened 
the conference attended by several hundred poles and jewish 
visitors coincided with the 45th anniversary of the ghetto 
uprising when jews held off the final nazi extermination drive for 
nearly a month 
it was attended by several polish government ministers senior 
polish communist party officials roman catholic bishops as well as 
jews from israel the united states and other western countries 
but the discussions onstage and in the corridors thursday and 
friday only showed that 45 years later jews and poles still find 
it difficult to talk with each other about the past 
israel gutman professor of jewish history at the hebrew 
university in jerusalem took sharp issue with what he called 
disastrous papers by some polish historians who claim the 
predominantly roman catholic poles played an active role in aiding 
residents of the jewish ghetto 
to my regret only a very small part of that is identical with 
the truth he said 
gutman is one of the few living survivors of the uprising in 
which hundreds of poorly armed jews fought a heroic but doomed 
threeweek battle resisting the final nazi drive to liquidate the 
ghettos last 70000 inhabitants 
the true picture is that until a certain period of time there 
was no contact between jews and nonjews said gutman who 
survived auschwitz and other nazi concentration camps before 
emigrating to israel after the war 
there was not help they poles did not lift a finger to help 
the hungry people in the ghetto gutman in an interview later 
in his conference paper gutman said the polish underground did 
not begin organized assistance for the ghetto until late 1942 
nearly two years after the nazis sealed off nearly 450000 jews 
within the ghetto walls 
most of them died of hunger disease or in the gas chambers of 
treblinka and other death camps 
kazimierz kakol chairman of the polish government commission 
for the investigation of nazi war crimes blamed the western powers 
for remaining deaf to calls to rescue polish jews despite 
receiving reports smuggled out by the polish underground about the 
nazis systematic annihilation of more than three million polish 
jews 
we poles did our utmost to help jews in their hour of 
death kakol said in a speech to the conference 
if the assistance was little it was because the possibilities 
for assistance were so small he said stressing that poles faced 
the death penalty from their nazi occupiers if they assisted jews 
some jews at the conference expressed outrage at what they 
considered attempts to distort the picture of polish assistance to 
jews 
