the us government acted improperly when it 
denied the widow of former chilean president salvador allende a 
visa in 1983 by saying the speeches she planned to give were a 
potential threat to foreign policy a federal appeals court has 
ruled 
the 1st us circuit court of appeals upheld a lower court 
ruling that denying a visa to hortensia allende violated the 1952 
immigration and nationality act 
but the court also noted that after the lawsuit was filed the 
government approved a multiple entry visa for mrs allende valid 
through the end of 1987 and has said it presumably would approve a 
visa application in 1988 
mrs allende has visited the united states several times under 
the visa said one of her attorneys allan rosenberg 
the court rejected the reagan administrations argument that 
mrs allendes presence would cause general harm to foreign 
policy 
the government may not exclude allende on the bare assertion 
that her presence in the united states at any given time may 
prejudice foreign policy interests the court said in a decision 
wednesday upholding a us district court ruling last year 
mrs allende had planned to address several groups in california 
that had invited her to speak on womens and human rights issues 
her husband salvador allende was slain during a 1973 coup that 
overthrew him and his marxist government 
the case was brought by the national emergency civil liberties 
