<TEXT>
fortyfive years after us fighter 
pilots killed the mastermind of the japanese attack on pearl 
harbor american survivors of the mission dispute who actually shot 
down admiral isoroku yamamoto 
yamamoto was killed april 18 1943 when american fighter planes 
intercepted his bomber near the solomon islands capt thomas g 
lanphier jr of detroit who died last year was credited by the 
military with the kill 
but the eight survivors among the 16 americans who carried out 
the mission said at a reunion saturday that they could not 
corroborate the official account because they had not been 
debriefed immediately after the attack 
they said they also could not determine how many japanese zero 
fighters accompanying yamamotos bomber were shot down 
at this time its a toss up on who shot down the betty 
bomber carrying admiral yamamoto which one was he in we didnt 
know at that point said ret lt col besby frank holmes of san 
francisco the passage of years hasnt clarified the subject 
these accounts add great confusion to the subject 
i wish there would have been a debriefing years ago he 
added 
holmes and the seven other survivors spoke at a symposium along 
with one of the japanese zero pilots 
the gathering was held here because fredericksburg is the home 
of admiral chester nimitz nimitz and his superiors approved the 
mission after the americans broke japans code and learned that 
yamamoto was going to be in the solomon islands 
yamamoto planned the japanese raid on pearl harbor on dec 7 
1941 that triggered the united states entry into world war ii 
capt roger pineau a retired naval intelligence officer said 
yamamotos death gave the american war effort a major boost 
in addition to the strategic and tactical effects of the shoot 
down of yamamoto it was a fantastic morale blow to the japanese 
people pineau said there was mourning in japan after the 
announcement of his death like is seldom seen except for emperors 
he was highly thought of 
the americans attacked two japanese bombers one carrying 
yamamoto and the other his chief of staff vice admiral matome 
ugaki the bombers were escorted by six zeros 
holmes said he shot down the bomber carrying ugaki and ret 
col rex barber of culver ore claimed on saturday he shot down 
yamamotos plane 
holmes said fights broke out after other pilots challenged their 
account of the number of zeros shot down 
kenji yanagiya the lone zero pilot at saturdays gathering 
added to the controversy when he said through an interpreter that 
all six zeros made it back to base safely that brought jeers from 
a crowd of about 400 
of the 16 americans on the mission one was listed as missing in 
action two died during later combat and five have died since the 
war 
items once belonging to yamamoto were unveiled in a new exhibit 
saturday at the nimitz museum here including swords yamamoto gave 
to his men with the inscription the fate of japans future 
depends on the outcome of this war 
the items were loaned by kansas city mo resident bernard 
brannon whose brother attorney john brannon acquired them after 
world war ii 
john brannon who died last year defended japanese naval 
officers charged with war crimes in return for his services the 
japanese officers gave him some of yamamotos personal items said 
bruce smith superintendent of the admiral nimitz state historical 
park 
