<TEXT>
trade ministers from the 
united states canada japan and the european community met in 
seclusion saturday for talks on issues ranging from patent 
protection to japanese quotas on us beef 
the weekend quadrilateral meeting held twice annually took 
place at a lodge on quadra island near vancouver the ministers 
hold a final news conference sunday 
a dozen peaceful protesters against the uscanada free trade 
agreement negotiated last year but not yet ratified stood on the 
road outside the lodge 
the focus of saturdays meeting was progress in the current 
round of talks within the general agreement on tariffs and trade 
the 95nation body governing world trade that was set up in 1948 
the trade negotiations involving 15 subgroups began in 
september 1986 and are scheduled for a comprehensive review in 
montreal in december 
those talks have the most ambitious negotiating agenda in the 
history of the world trade group us trade representative 
clayton yeutter said in a prepared text for a speech delivered 
friday to the vancouver board of trade 
yeutter was joined for the quadrilateral meeting by trade 
ministers hajime tamura of japan john crosbie of canada and willy 
de clercq of the 12national european community 
the reagan administration joined by canada is pressing for new 
general agreement on tariffs and trade rules to cover services such 
as insurance and computer software traderelated investment 
agriculture and protection for patents copyrights and trademarks 
increasingly countries are resorting to export subsidies and 
nontariff import barriers to achieve advantages over their 
competitors yeutter said 
yeutter said he also is looking for prompt japanese action to 
relax tough quotas for us beef and citrus products or washington 
will press a formal complaint with the 95nation group 
canadian trade official sylvia ostry said the erosion of open 
trading principles made the current general agreement on tariffs 
and trade round critical 
the outcome of this round will determine the outcome of the 
multilateral trading system period she said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

