<TEXT>
after four years of bitter conflict with frank 
lorenzo and his airline empire aviation labor is getting the 
sweeping government investigation it wanted 
but transportation department officials reject suggestions by 
lorenzo and his texas air corp that the probe announced wednesday 
is unioninspired 
officials say instead a series of financial red flags and 
texas airs own request for approval to spin off eastern airlines 
lucrative northeast shuttle put senior department analysts on the 
alert 
with that backdrop the deciding factor that triggered the 
unprecedented investigation say department officials was word 
from the federal aviation administration of continuing safety 
violations at eastern airlines 
other carriers have been in precarious financial positions in 
the past and others have had safety violations in the past but 
were not aware of a carrier having both come together this way at 
the same time said matthew scocozza whose dot office monitors 
the major airlines 
the broad investigation of texas air and its two subsidiary 
airlines eastern and continental stunned executives at the 
houstonbased airline company texas air stock dropped 150 per 
share to 1025 in two days and executives at both eastern and 
continental worried what impact the publicity would have on 
customers 
but the turmoil surrounding texas air has been years in the 
making 
lorenzo gained the wrath of organized aviation labor in 1983 
when he shut down continental airlines threw out its labor 
contracts and within days started a new airline with employees 
earning 50 percent less since texas air purchased eastern airlines 
in 1986 there have been continuous and rancorous confrontations 
over management demands for deep labor concessions 
lorenzo blames his troubles with labor for the government probe 
there is no question that this issue is founded in an 
oldfashioned labor dispute said a corporate statement the 
union leaderships have mounted a continuing campaign of 
distortion and lies it is unfortunate that this campaign has 
swayed others into action 
eastern airlines put advertisements into major newspapers the 
day after the investigation was announced saying it welcomed the 
probe and hoped it would clear the air about the unions charges 
and show unfair treatment of eastern by the faa 
on sunday texas air put a fullpage advertisement in several 
major newspapers that featured an editorial from fridays new york 
times the editorial concluded texas air has offended organized 
labor the industry establishment and a lot of important people in 
washington the airline has also irritated a lot of travelers 
it would be a pity though if these complaints distracted 
attention from texas airs constructive role in forcing a 
selfsatisfied cartelminded industry to come to terms with 
competition 
ironically the order to investigate texas air came from a 
transportation department that over the years has been considered 
anything but friendly to labor in nearly two dozen airline 
mergers the department not once has approved formal 
laborprotection provisions sought by the unions 
while the department denies being forced into action by labor 
there is little doubt that the unions wellfinanced and determined 
campaign drew the governments attention 
the faas intense look at eastern airlines last year for 
example was in part prompted by union reports of alleged 
maintenance and safety violations including charges repeated at 
congressional hearings that management was trying to force crews to 
fly unsafe aircraft 
pilots began sending postcards to aviation committees in 
congress the faa and its parent dot whenever there were 
maintenance problems with eastern planes 
labor challenges in court to the transfer of the northeast 
shuttle from eastern into a separate texas air subsidiary also 
caused dot officials concern after a federal judge came down on the 
