<TEXT>
james e olsons sudden absence from the helm of 
american telephone amp telegraph co due to cancer has raised 
unsettling questions about how companies prepare for abrupt 
management changes and tragedies at the top 
to a lesser extent the episode also has underlined the 
responsibility a public corporation faces not only to employees 
but shareholders in disclosing that a boss is ill or incapacitated 
such information can affect stock values 
responding to press queries about olsons rumored ill health 
atampt said last monday that the 62yearold chairman and chief 
executive officer was recuperating at home after colon cancer 
surgery march 25 the telecommunication giants stock fell 25 cents 
a share to 2787 in heavy trading 
company officials said they had not promptly disclosed olsons 
disease because it wasnt clear at the time that he faced a 
longterm incapacity 
moreover they said the delegation of authority in olsons 
absence was clearly understood because he had created a fivemember 
office of the chairman robert allen president and chief operating 
officer is running atampt for now and there is no question that 
olsons outline for its future remains unchanged 
despite the outwardly smooth transition in atampts case such 
crises almost always have an impact on companies especially those 
that arent prepared for them management experts say 
there isnt much catastrophe preparation of that sort its 
not seen as that consequential especially in larger companies 
where there is an obvious chain of command like the government 
said leonard sayles a professor of management at columbia business 
school 
the more serious problem that should be taken into account is 
how do you reassure people particularly at more senior levels 
that if there is a true disaster there are continuities sayles 
said they need assurances that a successor has the same values 
as a former ceo 
some say the management style of an incapacitated boss also 
plays an important role in how a company fares in his or her 
absence the most vulnerable companies are those run by managers 
who dont relinquish authority 
when entertainment conglomerate mca incs autocratic chief 
executive lew wasserman was hospitalized last summer for example 
speculation swirled about his health and the company became a 
takeover target forcing it to take steps to thwart any unwelcome 
suitors 
though wasserman 74 has given no indication he plans to 
retire he has since made clear that his successor would be sidney 
sheinberg president and chief operating officer who has been with 
the company for 14 years 
a serious management crisis befell gulf amp western industries 
inc five years ago when its handson leader charles bluedorn died 
of a heart attack while returning from a business trip nobody was 
prepared to replace him 
that corporation was totally thrown into a barrel of writhing 
question marks said gerald meyers a management consultant and 
former chairman of the defunct american motors corp it took them 
a long time to get sorted out 
meyers who has written a book titled when it hits the fan 
detailing management crises and how to avoid them estimated in a 
telephone interview that only about 150 of the fortune 500 
industrial companies have good contingency plans in the event of a 
chiefs death or incapacity 
its just a part of that overall mentality that we carry 
around with us he said we plan for success we allow no 
negative thoughts to invade our thinking and we get rid of people 
who bring up the possibilities as real as they may be that we 
could face difficulty with that formula its a surefire 
prescription for chaos if you face an event like that and youre 
unprepared 
the impact of tragedy at the top is lessened considerably when 
the burden of management is shared as in atampts case 
another good example was the passage of power at singer co when 
its chairman and chief executive joseph b flavin died suddenly 
last october 
flavin who had helped transform singer from a sewingmachine 
and furniture maker into a leading aerospaceelectronics concern 
was replaced immediately by its president and chief operating 
officer william f schmied 
there was nothing that went on in singer in terms of a 
management process that bill schmied hadnt been involved in 
thats the kind of thing most companies hope for said singer 
spokesman thomas l elliott it was an exceedingly smooth 
transition though it was a shocking event for all of us 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

